This is a great AI project for a student! Since you are using Python, you have access to powerful libraries that make resume parsing, ATS scoring, and job aggregation straightforward. 
1. Resume Parsing & ATS Analysis
To "get screened through the ATS," your app needs to extract text and analyze it like a recruiter. 
Text Extraction: Use PyMuPDF or pdfplumber to convert PDF resumes into raw text.
Information Extraction: Use spaCy or pyresparser to identify entities like Skills, Education, and Experience.
ATS Scoring: You can implement a scoring system based on:
Keyword Matching: Counting overlaps between the resume and a job description.
Semantic Similarity: Using SentenceTransformer or cosine similarity to see how well the meaning of the resume matches the job requirements. 
2. Job Aggregation & Matching
To bring all job links to one place, data needs to be collected from the web. 
Job APIs: Use APIs that aggregate jobs:
Adzuna API: High-quality job board aggregator.
Jooble API: A global job search engine.
Arbeitnow API: Good for remote and European jobs.
Matching Logic: Use TF-IDF or Large Language Models (LLMs) like GPT-4o or Gemini to rank the aggregated jobs by how "suitable" they are for the user's specific resume. 
3. Core Tech Stack (Python-Focused)
Component 	Recommended Tool
Backend	FastAPI or Flask (Standard for Python web apps)
Frontend	Streamlit (Fastest way for AI students to build a UI) or React
NLP/AI	spaCy, scikit-learn, SentenceTransformers
Database	SQLite or PostgreSQL to store user profiles and jobs
4. Implementation Roadmap
Build a simple Python script to extract text from a PDF and list extracted skills.
Connect to one Job API (like Adzuna) and fetch job listings based on those skills.
Write a function to calculate a "match score" (0–100%) between the resume and each job listing.
Wrap it in a Streamlit UI so users can upload their resume and see a list of matched job links. 


